{
 "cells": [
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Tutorial: Transform Faces with MediaPipe & GStreamer\n",
    "\n",
    "Welcome! This notebook is a beginner-friendly guide to using the **Mediapipe GStreamer Plugins**. Even if you have never used Docker or facial tracking before, this guide will help you transform images and videos in minutes.\n",
    "\n",
    "### What are we going to do?\n",
    "Facial transformation works in three main steps:\n",
    "1.  **Detection**: The AI finds 478 specific points on the face (called \"Landmarks\").\n",
    "2.  **Mapping**: We decide which points should move. For example, to make someone smile, we move the corners of the mouth upward.\n",
    "3.  **Warping**: A mathematical algorithm (MLS) stretches the pixels of the image to follow the moving points, creating a realistic effect.\n",
    "\n",
    "### The Tools We Use\n",
    "- **Docker**: A tool that runs our software in a \"controlled box\" (called a Container). This means you don't have to install complex AI libraries on your computer; they are already inside our **Docker Image**.\n",
    "- **Python Wrapper**: A simple script (`mozza_process.py`) that talks to Docker for you, so you only need to type short commands.\n",
    "\n",
    "---"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 1. Getting Started with Docker\n",
    "\n",
    "### Step A: Install Docker\n",
    "Before running any code, you need **Docker Desktop** installed and running on your computer. Think of it as a player for our \"box of software.\"\n",
    "- [Download for Windows](https://docs.docker.com/desktop/install/windows-install/)\n",
    "- [Download for Mac](https://docs.docker.com/desktop/install/mac-install/)\n",
    "- [Download for Linux](https://docs.docker.com/desktop/install/linux-install/)\n",
    "\n",
    "### Step B: Verify Docker\n",
    "Run the cell below. If you see a version number (like `Docker version 24.0.0`), you are ready!"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# The '!' symbol tells the notebook to run this as a system command.\n",
    "!docker --version"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Step C: NVIDIA GPU (Optional)\n",
    "Our plugins can run on your **CPU** (works everywhere) or your **NVIDIA GPU** (super fast). If you have an NVIDIA card, run this to see if it's detected:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# If this returns a table with GPU names, you can use the '--mode gpu' flag later.\n",
    "!nvidia-smi"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 2. Setup: Pull the \"Software Box\" (Docker Image)\n",
    "\n",
    "We have already built and uploaded the plugins to a central registry called Docker Hub. Run this to download it. It is about 3GB, so it might take a moment depending on your internet speed."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# 1. Pull the image from the cloud repository\n",
    "!docker pull ducksouplab/mp_plugins:latest\n",
    "\n",
    "# 2. Give it a short nickname ('mp_plugins') so we don't have to type the full name every time.\n",
    "!docker tag ducksouplab/mp_plugins:latest mp_plugins:latest"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Download the MediaPipe Model\n",
    "The plugins need one last piece: the AI \"brain\" file. This tells the software how to recognize a face."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# This helper script fetches the model file (.task) from Google and puts it in your folder.\n",
    "!cd .. && chmod +x download_face_landmarker_model.sh && ./download_face_landmarker_model.sh"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 3. Step 1: Detect Landmarks\n",
    "\n",
    "Let's see what the AI sees! We will take an image from the `assets/` folder and draw the 478 landmarks on it."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import os\n",
    "from IPython.display import Image, display, Video\n",
    "\n",
    "# Define where all our files are located\n",
    "tutorial_dir = os.getcwd()\n",
    "root_dir = os.path.abspath(os.path.join(tutorial_dir, \"..\"))\n",
    "wrapper_script = os.path.join(root_dir, \"mozza_process.py\")\n",
    "assets_dir = os.path.join(root_dir, \"assets\")\n",
    "model_path = os.path.join(root_dir, \"face_landmarker.task\")\n",
    "\n",
    "# Input: our original image\n",
    "input_img = os.path.join(assets_dir, \"test_image.jpg\")\n",
    "# Output: where we will save the result\n",
    "output_img = os.path.join(tutorial_dir, \"tutorial_landmarks.png\")\n",
    "\n",
    "# Run the command:\n",
    "# --mode landmarks: Only do detection, no warping.\n",
    "# --model-path: Use the AI brain we just downloaded.\n",
    "!python3 {wrapper_script} --input {input_img} --output {output_img} --mode landmarks --model-path {model_path}\n",
    "\n",
    "# Show the result here in the notebook!\n",
    "display(Image(filename=output_img))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 4. Step 2: Make Someone Smile (CPU Mode)\n",
    "\n",
    "Now we will use the **CPU plugin** to deform the image. We use a **DFM file** (`smile.dfm`), which is just a text file with instructions on which landmarks to pull. \n",
    "\n",
    "**Why CPU?** Because it works on every computer and requires zero configuration. It is perfect for processing photos and videos that aren't \"live.\""
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "deform_path = os.path.join(root_dir, \"smile.dfm\")\n",
    "output_cpu = os.path.join(tutorial_dir, \"tutorial_smile_cpu.png\")\n",
    "\n",
    "# Important settings:\n",
    "# --mode cpu: Runs on your processor.\n",
    "# --alpha 2.0: Intensity. '1.0' is normal, '2.0' is double. Try '-1.0' for a frown!\n",
    "# --warp-mode per-group-roi: Only warp the mouth area. This prevents the ears or background from stretching.\n",
    "# --show-landmarks false: Hide the dots so it looks realistic.\n",
    "!python3 {wrapper_script} --input {input_img} --output {output_cpu} \\\n",
    "    --mode cpu --deform {deform_path} --alpha 2.0 --warp-mode per-group-roi --show-landmarks false --model-path {model_path}\n",
    "\n",
    "# Show the transformation\n",
    "display(Image(filename=output_cpu))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 5. Step 3: Process a Video\n",
    "\n",
    "Processing video is exactly the same as images! The script will automatically detect the video format and encode the result as a high-quality MP4 file."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "input_video = os.path.join(assets_dir, \"dynamic_video.mp4\")\n",
    "output_video = os.path.join(tutorial_dir, \"tutorial_video_smile.mp4\")\n",
    "\n",
    "# We use a slightly more natural alpha (1.5) for the video.\n",
    "!python3 {wrapper_script} --input {input_video} --output {output_video} \\\n",
    "    --mode cpu --deform {deform_path} --alpha 1.5 --warp-mode per-group-roi --show-landmarks false --model-path {model_path}\n",
    "\n",
    "# Play the transformed video!\n",
    "display(Video(output_video, width=600, embed=True))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 6. Advanced Customization\n",
    "\n",
    "### A. How to change the intensity\n",
    "The `--alpha` parameter is your main control. \n",
    "- `0.0`: No effect.\n",
    "- `1.0`: Standard deformation.\n",
    "- `2.0+`: Strong, exaggerated deformation.\n",
    "- Negative values: Moves the points in the opposite direction.\n",
    "\n",
    \"### B. How the DFM file works\\n\",
    \"If you open `smile.dfm` in a text editor, you'll see lines like:\\n\",
    \"`0, 61, 146, 91, 61, -0.55, -0.55, 2.10`\\n\",
    \"\\n\",
    \"This is a **Rule**. It tells the software:\\n\",
    \"1.  Find landmark `61` (left mouth corner).\\n\",
    \"2.  Look at landmarks `146`, `91`, and `61` (these are \\\"anchors\\\").\\n\",
    \"3.  Calculate a target point based on where those anchors are right now.\\n\",
    \"4.  Pull the mouth corner toward that target.\\n\",
    \"\\n\",
    \"**Landmark Map:** To find the indices for other parts of the face (like eyes or eyebrows), refer to the [MediaPipe Face Mesh Map](https://storage.googleapis.com/mediapipe-assets/documentation/visualization/face_mesh_full_landmark_connections.png).\\n\",
    \"\\n\",
    \"You can create your own DFM files to enlarge eyes, change jawlines, or create any facial expression you can imagine!\\n\",

    "\n",
    "### C. Common Fixes\n",
    "- **Artifacts/Stretching**: If parts of the face look like they are \"bleeding\" into each other, increase `--mls-alpha`. This makes the skin act stiffer.\n",
    "- **Jitter/Shaking**: If the smile jumps around in video, use `--smooth 0.7` (available in `--mode gpu`). This will average the movement over several frames to make it steady."
   ]
  }
 ],
